<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the Heritage Railway Association (SLC 010)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Written evidence f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">rom the Heritage Railway Association</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> (SLC 010)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In principle, level crossings on the national network and on heritage lines should present a similar image and operation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to lessen the risk of confusion by road users.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nonetheless, it should be borne in mind that the lower operating speeds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">higher </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">noise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">trains on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heritage railways reduce the risk of hazard to other crossing users.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Anticipated Law Commission </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recommendations to repeal the Level Crossings Act 1983 and to extend the application of the general duty of care under the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974 are not supported.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The cost of upgrading crossings to take account of local developments giving ri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se to increased road traffic should be borne by the highway authority or relevant developer.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Committee’s question 3 implies the existence of a national rail budget.   Heritage railways are privately funded.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Committee’s questions 3 and 5 imply that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the onus for level crossing safety is on railways alone, rather than on highway authorities or road users.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Heritage Railway Association (HRA)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HRA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">represents 108 heritage railways </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and tramways </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and 60 steam centres around the United Kingdom and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The HRA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provides advice and guidance to members on changes in legislation and regulation and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n safety of operations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a forum for sharing good practice as well as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">marketing and promotion. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The HRA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">run entirely by volunteers, and make</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s good use of those with previous experience of the rail industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and of government and re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ulation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   In aggregate, member railways and tramways operate 527 miles of track and 408 stations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">making</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 15 million passenger journeys</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A recent report by t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he All Party Parliamentary Group on Heritage Rail estimated the value of heritage railways and tramways to the UK economy as £250m pa and the sector supports 3,700 jobs as well as attracting 18,500 volunteers.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Safety</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Safety is the priority for all heritage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> railways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and many of the requirements for the main li</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e network are also applicable on heritage lines, such as the establishment of safety management systems, the reporting of incidents (RIDDOR) and competency training, particularly for staff undertaking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">safety critical work. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The approach reflects </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> particular characteristics </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of heritage railways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> volunteers and the use of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">traditional railway </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">equipment. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Close contact is maintained between HRA and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Director of Rail Safety and his staf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Office of Rail Regulation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and details of safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">guidance and accident reports, together with the lessons learned are circulated to all members to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensure they are kept up to date.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Level Crossings</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As on the national rail system, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there are many level crossings on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heritage railways, varying from traditional gated crossings under the control of a signalman to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">locally monitored </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">automatic open</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and barrier-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">protected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as well as occupation and footpath crossings.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These have tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aditionally been subject to the same rules and regulations as those on the national network, even though </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">train </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">speed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on heritage railways </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> limited to 25 mph.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This speed may be further reduced at level crossings if required by local circumstances, such as the sighting distance.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The arrangements at each </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">public road </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossing are governed by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local legislation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, specific to each crossing, approved by a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">epartment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ransport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> official after inspection by HM</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Railway Inspectorate, which arrangements we fully endorse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Safety at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">farm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and footpath crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> managed through a risk assessment process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> carried out by the railway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are three key differences between the conditions of heritage and main line train operation.  </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The speed on heritage railways is limited to 25mph</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In general, more staff are around on heritage railways to observe train running and report or react to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any abnormality.  Steam trains require a crew of two, which is a benefit in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">watching for any hazards on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> approaching crossings.    </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Steam locomotives and heritage diesels tend to be more visible and noisier than quiet, modern trains</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which means th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">road</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> users are more likely to be aware of their presence.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nevertheless, accidents have occurred at level crossings on heritage railways and require continued and constant vigilance to improve safety.  Maintenance of the highway, warning signs, and regul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ar cutting back of vegetation to improve sightlines are all examples of work undertaken to keep both rail and road users safe, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">although not all highway authorities appear to recognise th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at some of this work is th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eir </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">responsibilit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst train operators are well aware of the risks associated with the use of level crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we recognise the need to raise awareness amongst road users.  In particular, our railways often operate in holiday areas where car drivers may be unfamiliar with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, or indeed may not encounter a level crossing on the routes they normally travel.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  In these circumstances, holidaymakers are in a relaxed frame of mind, and may not be focused on the need for vigilance when using crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Proposed Change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s to Level Crossing Legislation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We understand that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Law Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> propose to revise the law in relation to level crossings, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">replacing the present system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which sets out </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">specific requirements in a bespoke </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evel </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rossing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rder with a general duty of care under the Health </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Safety at Work Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, 1974</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For heritage railways, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we believe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that if th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> were to be adopted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cause significant problems as it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">replace specific requirement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s on methods </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of operation and signage,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which the railway can plan to meet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with a general duty of care</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Each</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> railway </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have to undertake new risk assessments at every level crossing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> against unspecific criteria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we are concerned that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be open to chall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enge in the courts in the event of any accident or incident, even when result</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">use by the road user.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">impose a significant workload </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and risk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on our member railways which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have limited resources and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are predominantly staffed by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">volunteers.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Moreover, while it is clearly feasible to impose the general duty of care on railway and highway authorities, it is not obvious how the private motorist, cyclist or pedestrian could be brought within its scope.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The desire to simplify legisla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tion relating to level crossings is understood, but the effect will result in additional cost and complexity for heritage railways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It is one of a number of examples of unintended consequences of legislation and regulation designed for the national networ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">k affecting heritage railways.  Since the Transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Works Act, 1992, and the Railways Act of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1993</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, HRA has had to make representations on many occasions to ensure that legislative and regulatory changes do not result in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">additional and inappropriate bur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">den</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> heritage lines which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ould </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increase costs and complexity unnecessarily</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In practical terms, we are also concerned at the possible practical problems in disapplying the existing legislative provisions as generally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local Acts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ight </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ailway </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rders </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ransport and Works</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rders cover other associated issues and deal with more than level crossing protection.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cost Allocation</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aintenance and operation of level crossings fall as a cost on the railway concerned, and this includes upgrading the crossing o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r providing additional safeguards where circumstances change.  Such changes usually occur as a result of increased road traffic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> often driven by developments increasing use on what had previously been a quiet rural road.  This is inherently inequitable, requiring significant investment by a small private company supported by a volunteer workforce to fund the consequences of additio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nal traffic resulting from developments which may yield significant profits for the commercial companies concerned.  We believe that developers should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the cost of any consequential upgrade resulting from a development, and that local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">highway authoriti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he cost where the increase is attributable to a general </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">road</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">traffic increase in the area.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Tramways</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We understand that the Law Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will recommend that level crossing legislation should not apply to tramways, since they operate on si</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ght, mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">v</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e at slower speeds and their vehicles are lighter in weight than those o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> railways.   We would endorse this approach.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Questions Raised by the Committee</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Are current safety measures at level crossings adequate? How should they be improved? </span></li></ol><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.34pt; padding-left:1.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">general, level crossings are safe if used responsibly by both train operator and road user.  Few accidents are caused by equipment failure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> most result from human error.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">However, it is true that any level crossing provides the potential for conflict betwe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">en road and rail traffic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition to bridges and underpasses what other cost-effective measures can be introduced to replace or improve safety at level crossings?  </span></li></ol><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.34pt; padding-left:1.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In some cases it is possible to achieve improvements by diverting roads or footpaths over nearby bridges. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How should expenditure on improving safety at level crossings be prioritised in relation to other demands on the rail budget?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.34pt; padding-left:1.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It is assumed that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he “rail budget” is related to the funding provided by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">overnment.   Heritage railways receive no such funding and are reliant on private resources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to effect changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Is Network Rail giving sufficient priority to improving safety at level </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossings?</span></li></ol><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.34pt; padding-left:1.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We support the work done by Network Rail to increase awareness of the risks at level crossings and to make users more aware of the potential hazards.  This clearly benefits awareness of the risks associated with crossings of heritage railways as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> well as those on the national network. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Is Government policy and regulatory action by the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety at level crossings adequate? What more should the Government and ORR do?</span></li></ol><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.34pt; padding-left:1.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The requirement is much wider than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the need for regulatory action on the rail industry alone.  It involves highway auth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rities and the road user and is about changing attitudes and behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">  This implies that government policy has not perhaps been sufficiently broadly based.  As indicated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> above, we do not believe that the present policy designed to simplify the law on level crossings will help to deliver a safer system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">for the heritage sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How should the legislation governing level crossings be updated?</span></li></ol><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.34pt; padding-left:1.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We do not believe that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">specific requirements at each location should be replaced by a general and non-specific requirement under the Health &amp; Safety at Work Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, 1974</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  The present system has been developed over many years and is very effective in setting out clearly what is req</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">uired to allow each crossing to be operated safely.   The alternative imports uncertainty, will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">result in a variety of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">solutions around the country</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, and the present consistency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">of approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">will be lost.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We believe it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">will mean that rail operators will be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">exposed to legal action and will find it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">difficult to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">secure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">highway authority or developer contributions, if the primary responsibility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> is left with them </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">specify</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> a safe system of operation.  We also believe that such an approach is impractical whe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">re level crossing safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">actually </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">depends on three parties – the rail operator, the highway authority and the road user</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, and not on the rail operator alone</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How should public awareness of safety at level crossings be improved?</span></li></ol><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 34.34pt; padding-left:1.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The good work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">in raising awareness, including advertising, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">undertaken by Network Rail should continue, but needs to be supported by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">similar commitment from highway authorities and other agencies concerned with ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">d safety.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">For example, it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ould </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">given more prominence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> in the questions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the driving test</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">highlighted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> in advice from Government on their “Think!” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">road safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">website.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>